Few mothers actually practice family planning. Focusing on changing custom and myths is important, and gives women a voice.

Empowering Women through Radio Programs

Eleven years ago, Iman Camara, M.D., Ph.D., Director of Democratic Voice of Vietnamese Women (D.V.V.W.) and I took on a project to deliver a health program to an impoverished region in Sudan through a mobile video van that stayed in one location per day over a period of two weeks. Between 2005 and 2010, D.V.V.W. recruited seven volunteer public health workers – women from Federation of Women Societies and Associations in Sudan. It has a budget of $30,000

The 2005 pilot project started with collecting health data in two large camps of internally displaced people from Besratan and Shangil Tobaya in the Nahr aElbared (Red Sea) state bordering East Sudan.

The vehicle was stationary for one day in each place during daytime. Placed on the spot, a video and audio projector beam medical films that raise awareness and provide information on many neglected health issues such as TB, epilepsy, malaria, tetanus neonatorum, early marriage and neonatal tetanus, lack of HIV/AIDS awareness
